```

Wait, perhaps even more directly, we can use the `native_decide` tactic after substituting all possible values for `x` and `y`.

Since `x` and `y` are `BitVec 3`, they can take values from 0 to 7. So, we can use `fin_cases` to do case analysis on all 8 possibilities for `x` and `y`.

```tactics
import Smt

open BitVec

theorem append_eq_shl_or_3 (x y : BitVec 3)
    : x ++ y = (x.zeroExtend 6 <<< 3#2) ||| y.zeroExtend 6 := by
  fin_cases x <;> fin_cases y <;> native_decide
```

This should work. `fin_cases x` will generate cases for `x` being 0, 1, ..., 7, and `fin_cases y` will do the same for `y`. For each of the 64 cases, `native_decide` will compute both sides and verify they are equal.

